{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"0a6ba933-e208-42f9-bf99-b68f8e779ef1","content":"I found **3 evaluation performance anti-patterns** in this project:\n\n### 1. File I/O Property Function (most impactful)\n**`EvalHeavy.csproj`, line 13:**\n```xml\n<BuildNotes>$([System.IO.File]::ReadAllText('build-notes.txt'))</BuildNotes>\n```\n`System.IO.File::ReadAllText` runs synchronous disk I/O during the property evaluation phase. This blocks the evaluator on every build. Move this to a target with `Inputs/Outputs` so it only runs when needed.\n\n### 2. Expensive Wildcard Glob\n**`EvalHeavy.csproj`, line 9:**\n```xml\n<AdditionalFiles Include=\"**\\*.*\" Exclude=\"**\\bin\\**;**\\obj\\**\" />\n```\n`**\\*.*` walks the entire directory tree at evaluation time. If large directories exist (e.g., `node_modules`, `.git`), this becomes very costly. Add known large directories to `DefaultItemExcludes` or narrow the glob to specific extensions.\n\n### 3. Deep Import Chain\n```\nEvalHeavy.csproj → level1.props → level2.props → level3.props\n```\nA 3-level chain (on top of SDK implicit imports). While manageable here, each import adds evaluation overhead. Flatten where possible — `level1.props` could import `level3.props` directly, or consolidate into fewer files.\n\n**Priority fix:** The `File::ReadAllText` call is the worst offender — property functions with I/O are the most expensive evaluation-time operation.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"b1a6c0b8-4d03-4af5-9391-424b81f02384","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"Now I have a complete picture of the project. Let me analyze the evaluation performance issues:\n\n1. **Deep import chain**: `EvalHeavy.csproj` → `level1.props` → `level2.props` → `level3.props` — a 3-level deep chain. While 3 levels isn't extreme, this pattern scales poorly.\n\n2. **Expensive glob pattern**: `<AdditionalFiles Include=\"**\\*.*\" Exclude=\"**\\bin\\**;**\\obj\\**\" />` — This walks the entire directory tree recursively, which is expensive during evaluation, especially if the directory tree is large (e.g., if node_modules, .git, or other large directories exist).\n\n\n3. **File I/O during evaluation**: The build is reading file contents synchronously through a property function during the property evaluation phase, which blocks and adds significant overhead.","outputTokens":633,"requestId":"7818:3C05D0:2168EF:298032:69F551BE"},"id":"23f64df0-3582-4ff4-a917-0904d1972e38","timestamp":"2026-05-02T01:22:20.381Z","parentId":"1288dd06-70e4-4feb-a8fc-fdbdccb32450"}
